 TeaTree drives the day from a single long-lived Claude Code session running a fat `/loop` (the `dedicated_loops = false` default of Track A above). The loop fires on a fixed cadence (default 12 minutes via `[teatree] loop_cadence_seconds`). The tick body is `teatree.loop.tick.run_tick` — code, not prose, so it is tested, typed, and version-controlled. `run_tick` composes named single-responsibility phases from `teatree.loop.phases` ([#1796](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/1796)): `scan_phase` (parallel world-scan), `sweep_phase` (split the maintenance scanners — `pr_sweep`/`self_update`/`pull_main_clone` — out of the scan), `act_phase` (dispatch + mechanical + persist), and `orchestrate_phase` (the speed-driven autonomous fan-out — a no-op at the default `medium` speed; `slow` admits at most one, `full`/`boost` clamp a claimed manifest to the per-overlay `max_concurrent_auto_starts` budget via the existing claim-next CAS, computing + returning the manifest only — spawning stays in the session/self-pump half). `run_tick` wires `orchestrate_phase` as a **read-only budget PLANNER** — it computes the clamped fan-out cap but never claims a `Task` row (`claim=False` always on the tick path). The reconciled fan-out ([#1796](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/1796) WI-1) keeps exactly ONE claim point, the live `claim_next` CAS, so the tick can never orphan a claim the live claimer also takes (the prior `claim=True` arm could). When the opt-in, default-OFF `[teatree] orchestrate_claim_enabled` toggle (per-overlay overridable, `T3_ORCHESTRATE_CLAIM_ENABLED` env override; the tick read degrades to OFF on any settings-read error) is ON **and** the speed clamps (`full`/`boost`/`slow`), the tick persists the computed cap as an admit-budget ceiling to the `tick-meta.json` sidecar (`teatree.loop.admit_budget`, beside the freshness/open-PR sidecars). The live claimer (`loop_dispatch claim-next`) reads that budget and refuses the marginal claim once the standing in-flight CLAIMED dispatchable WIP (`Task.objects.in_flight_claimed_count`) hits the ceiling — so claimed ≡ spawned. At `medium` OR with the toggle OFF, **no budget key is written** (any prior one is cleared): absence = unclamped = today's throughput, byte-identical. The reader carries a `written_at` TTL (~2× cadence) and fails open to unclamped on an absent/stale/corrupt budget, so a dead loop never wrongly throttles live dispatch ([#1838](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/1838) agent-teams Track-A; [#1917](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/1917) parent).
 
-**Agent-teams Track-B — the inert maker-only pane layer ([#1838](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/1838)).** A maker pane is a long-lived `team:<role>` claim (the PR#6 team-role registry, `teatree.teams.roles`) of the existing `Task` + lease — no new model, no migration. `teatree.teams` houses the lifecycle FSM (`panes.py`: `spawn → active → idle → stopped`, state DERIVED from the live `Task` claim + lease + the ticket's live `Session`), the idle-pane reaper (`pane_reaper.py`: demote any pane with no live `Session` past `[teams] idle_minutes` to stopped, fail-safe KEEP on uncertainty), and the loop-owner collision guardrails (`guardrails.py`: a hard claim-boundary guard that a pane claims ONLY `team:<role>` and can never claim `loop-owner` or a `loop:` slot — the proven disjoint key spaces are the backbone; plus a pre-work live-owner check that skips a pane while a live foreign `loop-owner` drives the loop). The pane budget is `[teams] max_panes` (default 1) and `[teams] idle_minutes` (default 30) on `UserSettings` — read from the `[teams]` table, per-overlay overridable, env-overridable via `T3_TEAMS_MAX_PANES` / `T3_TEAMS_IDLE_MINUTES`, each fail-safe to its default at every tier so the safety bound cannot be configured away. A pane heartbeats via the existing `Task.renew_lease`, so `reclaim_orphaned_claims` / `reap_stale_claims` still recover a dead pane's claim — the DB stays the source of truth. **Default-OFF**: `teams_enabled` defaults false, so the maker claim path and the pane reaper are no-ops and nothing spawns. The only live-path module that imports `teatree.teams` is the sanctioned pane-reaper scanner (`teatree.loop.scanners.pane_reaper`), which the pane-reaper mini-loop dispatches and which is itself gated `None`-when-off; the narrowed [#2320](https://github.com/souliane/teatree/issues/2320) AST scan pins that no OTHER live-path module wires the registry in. The lead's `SessionStart(source=compact)` ORPHANS the stale `loop-owner` lease (`session_id=""`, via `evict_stale_owner`) synchronously before any tick, so the lead's next `t3 loop tick` re-anchors `loop-owner` uncontested and no pane can win the compaction-window CAS race. The maker consumer (the SDK spawn helper `teatree.teams.pane_spawn` + the maker claim path + the pane-reaper mini-loop) lands here; REVIEWER panes are never spawnable (a code-level raise pinned by a fitness test), and reviewing stays on the fresh-spawn-per-head_sha AutoReviewDispatch path. **Pane DISPLAY layer (WI-5, presentation-only).** `teatree.teams.pane_display` is the optional half that renders a maker pane's in-process SDK session in a visible terminal pane — `spawn_pane` issues `tmux split-window -- claude --resume <session_id> --model <model> --permission-mode bypassPermissions` (the resumed id is `build_pane_options`'s resolved SDK session — the SAME session, the single source of truth) and titles the pane `team:<role>`. teatree only ever issues plain `tmux split-window` / `select-pane` / `kill-pane`; the NATIVE iTerm2 split rendering is purely a property of how the USER attached (`tmux -CC` control mode), so the same commands degrade to plain tmux panes elsewhere (mirroring Claude Code's own `teammateMode`). The display NEVER replaces the SDK run: no tmux / no TTY / any spawn failure falls back to the in-process path (`detect_multiplexer` is the probe; `spawn_pane` returns `None` on any failure). The in-pane `claude` child is plain interactive (NEVER `claude -p`), so it routes through the interactive-billing lane — a visible interactive pane is the intended path, not a metered-headless backdoor. Teardown is DB-driven: the pane-reaper scanner's demote-to-STOPPED triggers `reconcile_orphan_panes`, which `kill-pane`s every `team:*`-titled pane whose slot is no longer a live claim (the DB lease stays authoritative, tmux is a downstream effect), and the same reconcile reaps orphaned panes at startup. The mode is `[teams] display = "auto" | "tmux" | "none"` (`UserSettings.teams_display`, default `none` — per-overlay overridable, `T3_TEAMS_DISPLAY` env wins, a bad value fails safe to `none`). **Default-OFF (`none`) + headless/CI ⇒ byte-identical to today.** `pane_display` is a pure leaf imported on the live path only via the same sanctioned pane-reaper scanner, so the #2320 inertness scan stays green.
